{{family name hatnote|Kamo|lang=Japanese}} {{Infobox Japanese clan | surname nihongo = 賀茂氏 | image = File:Tokugawa family crest.svg | image size = 140px | image caption = [[Mon (emblem)|Mon]] of the Kamo clan | home province = [[Yamashiro Province|Yamashiro]] | founding year = 7th century |cadet branches=[[Miwa clan]](possibly only in legend)|founder=[[Kamo no Okimi]]}}
{{nihongo|'''Kamo clan'''|賀茂氏|Kamo-shi}} is a Japanese [[sacerdotal]] kin group<ref>Breen, John and Mark Teeuwen. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=MADlfH002mAC&pg=PA86 ''Shinto in History: Ways of the Kami,'' p. 86.]</ref> which traces its roots from a [[Yayoi period]] shrine in the vicinity of northeastern Kyoto.<ref>Shimogamo-jinja web site: [http://www.shimogamo-jinja.or.jp/english/index.html history.]</ref> The clan rose to prominence during the [[Asuka period|Asuka]] and [[Heian period|Heian]] periods when the Kamo are identified with the 7th-century founding of the [[Kamo Shrine]].<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric ''et al.'' (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA586 ''Japan Encyclopedia,'' p. 586.]</ref>
==Kamo Shrine== The Kamo Shrine's name references the area's early inhabitants, many of whom continue to live near the shrine their ancestors traditionally served.<ref>Nelson, John K. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=SPchlKNrj0UC&dq=kamo+clan&pg=PA92 ''Enduring Identities: The Guise of Shinto in Contemporary Japan,'' pp. 92-99.]</ref> The formal names of corollary ''jinja'' memorialize vital clan roots in a history which pre-dates the founding of Japan's ancient capital.<ref name="yomiuri1">Miyazaki, Makoto. [http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/columns/0005/lens170.htm "Lens on Japan: Defending Heiankyo from Demons,"] ''Daily Yomiuri.'' December 20, 2005.</ref>
The Kamo Shrine encompasses what are now independent but traditionally associated ''[[Shinto shrine|jinja]]'' or shrines—the {{Nihongo|Kamo-wakeikazuchi Shrine|賀茂別雷神社|''Kamo-wakeikazuchi jinja''}} in Kyoto's Kita Ward and; and the {{Nihongo|"Kamo-mioya Shrine'"|賀茂御祖神社|''Kamo-mioya jinja''}} in Sakyo Ward. The ''jinja'' names identify the various ''[[kami]]'' or deities who are venerated; and the name also refers to the ambit of shrine's nearby woods.<ref>Kamigamo-jinja web site: [http://www.kamigamojinja.jp/english/index-e.html about the shrine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221145021/http://kamigamojinja.jp/english/index-e.html |date=2009-02-21 }}.</ref>
[[File:Tadasu no mori 200906a.jpg|thumb|right|A wild vista unfolds at ''Tadasu no Mori''.]] Although now incorporated within boundaries of the city, the location was once ''[[Tadasu no Mori]]'' (糺の森),<ref>Terry, Philip. (1914). [https://books.google.com/books?id=9ipbUA13CHoC&dq=tadasu+no+mori&pg=PA479 ''Terry's Japanese empire,'' p. 479.]</ref> the wild forest home of the exclusive caretakers of the shrine from prehistoric times.<ref>Nelson, p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=SPchlKNrj0UC&dq=kamo+clan&pg=PA67 pp. 67-69.]</ref>
==Notable clan members== {{dynamic list}} * [[Kamo no Chōmei]] (1155–1216) * [[Kamo no Mabuchi]] (1697–1769)
Although [[Ieyasu Tokugawa]] never used the surname Tokugawa before 1566, his appointment as shōgun was contingent on his claim to Matsudaira kinship and a link to the [[Seiwa Genji]]. Modern scholarship has revealed that the genealogy proffered to the emperor contained falsified information; however, since the [[Matsudaira clan|Matsudaira]] used the same crest as the Kamo clan,<ref>Nussbaum, [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA34 ''Japan Encyclopedia,'' p. 34.]</ref> some academics suggest that he was likely a descendant of the Kamo clan."<ref>Plutschow, Herbert. (1995). [https://books.google.com/books?id=fNQjDQ-mWYgC&dq=plutschow+and+kamo&pg=PA158 "Japan's Name Culture: The Significance of Names in a Religious, Political and Social Context,'' p. 158.]</ref> ==Genealogy== {{Eight generations of Izumo}}
