<!--Kamo clan-->

{{family name hatnote|Kamo|lang=Japanese}} 
{{Infobox Japanese clan
| surname nihongo = 賀茂氏
| image           = File:Tokugawa family crest.svg
| image size      = 140px
| image caption   = [[Mon (emblem)|Mon]] of the Kamo clan
| home province   = {{ill|Yamashiro Province|en|Yamashiro Province|qid=Q749276|lt=Yamashiro|1=Yamashiro Province}}
| founding year   = 7th century
|cadet branches=[[Miwa clan]] (possibly only in legend),<br>
{{ill|Kadenokōji family|ja|勘解由小路家|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kadenokōji family|qq=}}|founder=[[Kamo no Okimi]]}}

{{nihongo|'''Kamo clan'''|賀茂氏|Kamo-shi}} is a Japanese [[:en:Sacerdotal|Sacerdotal]] kin group<ref>Breen, John and Mark Teeuwen. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=MADlfH002mAC&pg=PA86  ''Shinto in History: Ways of the Kami,'' p. 86.]</ref> which traces its roots from a {{ill|Yayoi period|en|Yayoi period|qid=Q207858|lt=Yayoi period|1=Yayoi period}} shrine in the vicinity of northeastern Kyoto.<ref>Shimogamo-jinja web site: [http://www.shimogamo-jinja.or.jp/english/index.html history.]</ref> The clan rose to prominence during the {{ill|Asuka period|en|Asuka period|qid=Q210688|lt=Asuka|1=Asuka period}} and {{ill|Heian period|en|Heian period|qid=Q193292|lt=Heian|1=Heian period}} periods when the Kamo are identified with the 7th-century founding of the [[Kamo shrines|Kamo Shrine]].<ref>Nussbaum, Louis-Frédéric ''et al.'' (2002). [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA586  ''Japan Encyclopedia,'' p. 586.]</ref>

==Kamo Shrine==
The Kamo Shrine's name references the area's early inhabitants, many of whom continue to live near the shrine their ancestors traditionally served.<ref>Nelson, John K. (2000). [https://books.google.com/books?id=SPchlKNrj0UC&dq=kamo+clan&pg=PA92  ''Enduring Identities: The Guise of Shinto in Contemporary Japan,'' pp. 92-99.]</ref>  The formal names of corollary ''jinja'' memorialize vital clan roots in a history which pre-dates the founding of Japan's ancient capital.<ref name="yomiuri1">Miyazaki, Makoto. [http://www.yomiuri.co.jp/dy/columns/0005/lens170.htm  "Lens on Japan: Defending Heiankyo from Demons,"] ''Daily Yomiuri.'' December 20, 2005.</ref>

The Kamo Shrine encompasses what are now independent but traditionally associated ''{{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=jinja|1=Shinto shrine}}'' or shrines—the {{Nihongo|Kamo-wakeikazuchi Shrine|賀茂別雷神社|''Kamo-wakeikazuchi jinja''}} in Kyoto's Kita Ward and; and the {{Nihongo|"Kamo-mioya Shrine'"|賀茂御祖神社|''Kamo-mioya jinja''}} in Sakyo Ward. The ''jinja'' names identify the various ''[[kami]]'' or deities who are venerated; and the name also refers to the ambit of shrine's nearby woods.<ref>Kamigamo-jinja web site: [http://www.kamigamojinja.jp/english/index-e.html about the shrine] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221145021/http://kamigamojinja.jp/english/index-e.html |date=2009-02-21 }}.</ref>

[[File:Tadasu no mori 200906a.jpg|thumb|right|A wild vista unfolds at ''Tadasu no Mori''.]]
Although now incorporated within boundaries of the city, the location was once ''[[Tadasu no Mori]]'' (糺の森),<ref>Terry, Philip. (1914). [https://books.google.com/books?id=9ipbUA13CHoC&dq=tadasu+no+mori&pg=PA479  ''Terry's Japanese empire,'' p. 479.]</ref> the wild forest home of the exclusive caretakers of the shrine from prehistoric times.<ref>Nelson, p.  [https://books.google.com/books?id=SPchlKNrj0UC&dq=kamo+clan&pg=PA67 pp. 67-69.]</ref>

==Notable clan members==
{{dynamic list}}
* {{ill|Kamo no Chōmei|en|Kamo no Chōmei|qid=Q291329|lt=Kamo no Chōmei|1=Kamo no Chōmei}} (1155–1216)
* [[Kamo no Mabuchi]] (1697–1769)

Although [[:en:Ieyasu Tokugawa|Ieyasu Tokugawa]] never used the surname Tokugawa before 1566, his appointment as shōgun was contingent on his claim to Matsudaira kinship and a link to the {{ill|Seiwa Genji|en|Seiwa Genji|qid=Q2164991|lt=Seiwa Genji|1=Seiwa Genji}}. Modern scholarship has revealed that the genealogy proffered to the emperor contained falsified information; however, since the {{ill|Matsudaira clan|en|Matsudaira clan|qid=Q1141077|lt=Matsudaira|1=Matsudaira clan}} used the same crest as the Kamo clan,<ref>Nussbaum, [https://books.google.com/books?id=p2QnPijAEmEC&pg=PA34  ''Japan Encyclopedia,'' p. 34.]</ref> some academics suggest that he was likely a descendant of the Kamo clan."<ref>Plutschow, Herbert. (1995). [https://books.google.com/books?id=fNQjDQ-mWYgC&dq=plutschow+and+kamo&pg=PA158  ''Japan's Name Culture: The Significance of Names in a Religious, Political and Social Context'', p. 158.]</ref>
